<subSubSection pageId="114" pageNumber="115" type="distinguishing features">
<paragraph pageId="114" pageNumber="115">Distinguishing features.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="114" pageNumber="115">Distinguished by the prominent spreading hairs on the calyx and often also on the stem and leaves.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="114" pageNumber="115" type="distribution">
<paragraph pageId="114" pageNumber="115">Distribution.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="114" pageNumber="115">
Morocco (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="115">Balls</emphasis>
2934, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="115">Lindberg</emphasis>
3902, 
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="115">
<normalizedToken originalValue="Gattefossé">Gattefosse</normalizedToken>
</emphasis>
3/8/1935), Algeria (
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="115">Cosson</emphasis>
9/6/1875). Reaches at least 2300 m in Morocco (Jury 17634). It is also widely cultivated and reported to have escaped in Sicily.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="114" pageNumber="115" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="114" pageNumber="115">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="114" pageNumber="115">
The flexuose peduncles, prominent bracteoles, essentially broadly oblong leaves and violet flowers make 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Viv., Fl. Libyc. Spec. 67. 1824. (Viviani" authorityYear="1824" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Convolvulaceae" genus="Convolvulus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Plantae" lsidName="Convolvulus sabatius" order="Solanales" pageId="114" pageNumber="115" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="sabatius">
<emphasis italics="true" pageId="114" pageNumber="115">Convolvulus sabatius</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
a relatively distinct species.
</paragraph>
